Step1: Step 1: Install GPG
GPG (GNU Privacy Guard) is an encryption tool used to generate keys, sign files, and verify signatures.
On Windows, GPG is installed using Gpg4win.
Step 2: Generate GPG Key Pair
Using the command gpg --gen-key, a public key and private key are generated.
•	Public key → shared with others
•	Private key → kept secret and protected using a passphrase
This key pair is required for creating and verifying digital signatures.
Step 3: Create a File to Sign
A text file is created that acts as the message or data to be signed.
Example: file.txt
This file represents the information whose authenticity and integrity must be ensured.
Step 4: Sign the File
The command gpg --sign file.txt is used to create a digital signature.
•	GPG hashes the file
•	The hash is encrypted using the private key
•	A new signed file (file.txt.gpg) is created
This signed file contains both the original data and the signature.
Step 5: Enter Passphrase
During signing, GPG asks for the passphrase of the private key.
This ensures that only the legitimate owner can create the digital signature.
Step 6: Verify the Signed File
The command gpg --verify file.txt.gpg is used to verify the digital signature.
•	GPG decrypts the signature using the public key
•	GPG hashes the received file again
•	Both hashes are compared
If both hashes match, the signature is valid.
Step 7: List GPG Keys
The command gpg --list-keys displays all public keys available in the system.
This helps in identifying the key used for signing and verification.





